         <abstract>
            <p>Although the accounting literature specifies two generally accepted methods for translating foreign currency balance sheets -- the current/noncurrent and the monetary/nonmonetary methods -- the reporting of multinational corporations is typically some hybrid mixture of the two. In addition, these corporations can choose whether to defer or recognize current translation gains and losses. Whether the dollar appreciates or depreciates relative to foreign currencies, the multinationals can often exploit these two kinds of latitudes to enhance their reported dollar profits.</p>
          </abstract>
